<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911007-0149</DOCNO><DOCID>911007-0149.</DOCID><HL>   Official of Failed Thrift   Gets 27-Month Term   For Fraud, Conspiracy</HL><DATE>10/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CFK</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   BOSTON -- A former executive vice president of now-defunctComFed Savings Bank was sentenced to 27 months in prison forbank fraud, making false statements and conspiracy.   Frank A. Buco was accused of defrauding ComFed byconcealing second mortgages from ComFed's underwritingdepartment, permitting unqualified buyers to receive 100%financing. He pleaded guilty to various charges in March.</LP><TEXT>   ComFed, which suffered huge losses because the slumpingeconomy turned many of its real estate loans bad and to alesser extent because of fraud, was declared insolvent andseized by federal regulators last December.</TEXT></DOC>